						<p><b>Hispanic New Year</b></p>

						<p>Hispanic New Year’s celebrations vary by country. In Spain it is known as
							<em>Nochevieja.</em> People wait to hear the church chimes in the public square, and at midnight they each eat twelve grapes to symbolize each chime. On the other hand, in Mexico, people light a colored candle, with the color symbolizing what they hope for in the New Year.
						</p>
